segments.text: Nobody could enter this door.
The guard wouldn't let them.
Without calling.
Without me calling him on the phone to get permission to come in.
But this time he called.
I was his office right next door to him.
But there was no door from my office directly in.
I had to come out in the hallway to get to his door.
He called me.
I came in, and as I entered the door, he was staying in the middle of the room.
He drew himself up straight and so straight that he actually bent over backwards in a very arrogant, accusative manner.
General Bond, why are you disciplining my orders?
I said, what do you mean, disciplining your orders, General?
I told you I didn't want you coming up in the front of this building, and you've been doing it for the last week.
And I guess that's the closest I came to going on.
And I just took a step forward towards him, and I took my hand and said, I will never park in front of your building again, General, and turn around and walk down.
That's the closest I ever came to
insulting a general, whether it's American, foreigner, or anybody.
I never talked to a superior like that.
Turned around and walked out.
Matter of fact, I went to my office, put my cap on, and went home.
I was just furious.
Of course, settled down.
And never heard any more about David.
And where'd you park?
Oh, I parked in the back.
I didn't want to cause any more trouble.
And I determined that I just wouldn't
I would not see General Bianchi any more than I had to then on.
Did you report this to your general?
No, no, not officially, no.
I later on told him the story.
I'll tell you more about this later on.
I had a talk with him once.
But it's things of this nature.
The way he talked to my men is insulting.
ironic, satirical remarks.
Is there an American officer here that can do this?
Gentlemen, would you stand up and speak in American English to your officers so they understand my instructions?
This type of thing.
Really?
Oh.
Well, that's enough of that.
We're taking too much time.
But I can assure you that it was one of the hardest jobs I have ever had in my life.
Three years?
Three years.
I took on a little project at home, building a model house.
I concentrated on physical therapy, you know, walked at night, getting in shape, exercising, anything to get my mind off of my job.
He would call me in at times and we'd have staff meetings and I was polite, he was polite.
These things didn't show up except at the Freeport Times.
His underling officers, the lower-ranking Italian officers, had a great deal of respect for him.
They all knew the type of General Bianchi was, and they were absolutely scared to death of him.
I have never seen officers so scared of a commander as that.
I have never seen those.
Just in utter fear when he spoke to them.
The man had some reasons for being this way, I'm sure.
First, he had severe glaucoma and was blind in one eye.
I'm sure this is one reason that he didn't go any further in his military career.
Now, this is all in defense of General Bianchi.
His wife, I loved her and felt so sorry for her.
She was German and just as sweet as she could be.
You'd never know that she lived with a man of this temperament.
I've seen him actually, you know, act around her as though he insulted her.
He didn't act like a gentleman around her.
You know, she'd call him around like a little puppy, this type of thing.
I'm spending too much time on this.
Anyway.
Tell me about the time that you finally told your commanding officer.
This was about after two years.
Incidentally, when General, very few times would the
F. South Commander, a four-star United States Navy Admiral, very few times would he ever come up and visit us at 5-8 Taff.
Only one or two times did General Swafford ever come up and visit 5-8 Taff, and we just didn't have many visitors at all, and it was all because of the personality of this man.
He was well known to be this type of person.
Effectiveness reports.
Final effectiveness report when I was reassigned from, oh, about a year, you know, each year I had to have one.
It was a year before I was reassigned, and I'm sure it had a lot to do with my being promoted to a major general in, still in that position when I retired.
It's the only time an American general, Air Force, or NATO that I know of, and I was told, was promoted from brigadier general to a major general.
It was the only time that a Brigadier General assigned to NATO was given a second star in that position.
He had called for a Brigadier General.
Do you feel that was because of the fact that you could relate?
I'm going to tell you what this was.
I saw my effectiveness report.
General Swofford sent me a copy of it when he sent it in at the end of the second year.
And it had to be endorsed by the Navy AFSAL commander because he was the chain of command.
They took it.
And it so happened this was the United States four-star athlete.
And his remarks just on the endorsement was, I agree absolutely with everything General Swofford says about General Bond.
And of course, it was outstanding.
It topped right down the right-hand side.
And his last sentence, we are indeed fortunate that we have a man like General Bond in this position in 5th ATF.
He knew what the situation was.
The chief of staff of 5th ATF under General Swofford was an Italian major general, whom I learned to love.
And he would ask me questions.
He says,
Bond, they never call you by your first name in Italy.
It's always, Bond, how is life up at 5-8-10?
And I said, well, they did much better.
And he'd laugh and put his arm on me and said, I understand.
But he said, you know, these things will change.
He knew what I was getting at.
It was well known.
And I was given full credit by General Swartford and General and Admiral, Admiral Russell, for keeping my mouth and my temper, I'm sure.
I am convinced no other journal was put up by him.
I'm convinced of it.
And that's the reason this other journal that I relieved, he had to leave.
He wouldn't even talk to this man.
He wouldn't even talk to him.
And it just couldn't go.
I mean, you had to get rid of him.
What happened to that man?
He wasn't reduced in rank or anything.
They just sent him back home, gave him another job.
He knew what the situation was.
But at any rate, I was, we had a NATO.
Well, tell me about when you talked to the general.
I am.
I'm going to tell you right now.
We had a NATO conference of shape up at Wiesbaden, Germany.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, Wiesbaden, Germany.
No, at Ramstein with ATF.
Okay.
And had a meeting there.
And, of course, this was all the key generals.
General Bianchi did not go.
He wouldn't go.
He was supposed to go to this conference.
He wouldn't go.
He sent me.
It was beneath his dignity to go to this meeting.
That's the way he looked at it.
He wouldn't go.
And I went.
And that night, you know, General Crawford had heard things, I'm sure.
And that night, as we come back to her after one of the dinner's social
John said, come on in and have a drink.
I went in.
John said, how you getting along up there?
I said, well, John said, sometimes it gets pretty rough.
He says, I think I know what you mean.
He said, tell me about it.
And I said, well, John, I'll tell you.
I said, this man, John, will be honest.
He is, without a doubt, close to being me.
I just laid my hair down and told him, without a doubt, this man is a typical bossess.
And I said, there's no doubt he hates America.
He said, well, I've heard a lot of stories about this.
He says, tell me.
He asked me questions like, what does he do?
How does he act?
And I told him.
And I called to his attention.
I said, you remember when you visited ATAP about a month ago?
You remember you came up and he first picked you up in the car.
And then we rode over to the club.
I mean, where the headquarters were.
They're going to put you up.
And...
You reached in to get your bag out of the back of the car, you know, and he reached in and said, oh, no, we'll have your bag taken care of, General Swofford, you don't need to do that.
And I said, I distinctly remember that you looked at him and reached in and said, I'll take care of my own bag.
That's what General Swofford did.
He laughed.
You know what I mean?
I said, now this stone is what I have to put up with.
I said, I let him know that, you know, I realized he knew what I was doing.
And General Swofford, he listened to me for a while.
And I told him about some of the colonels under me that were being reassigned.
You know, the tour was over and all.
They had stories with me, and they literally despised the man.
And it was a hard job really to put up with this gentleman.
And all I'm saying, I don't see how you do it.
I don't see how you do it.
But that decided the point.
But General Swofford asked this guy, and he said, well, try this.
I'll tell you what.
He said, I can reassign you if you want me to.
And he knew that I was having this hard time.
And I don't know, I may have shown him the face that I was, you know, it's too much of a struggling emotion.
He said, I can have you reassigned if you want to.
And he, nothing but from the standpoint of demoting me, but, you know, just, you know, relieving me of this horrible experience.
And you've already had it for two years?
Yeah.
And I said, no.
I said, I can handle it.
I said, I don't want to be reassigned.
I said, I can handle this job.
I'll take it.
I said, I don't want you reassigned.
He said, okay.
And I stayed with him.
Until your three-year tour was over?
Well, fortunately, he didn't stay there.
After a little over two years, he was replaced by a completely opposite type of a general.
Lieutenant, I mean, he's a major gentleman.
He's got his third story.
He was a diplomat in completely the other extremes.
And I only had another year to go, a little less than another year to go, so I was going to have a fine job, and I knew I had to be rotated.
But a terrific man, and he fully understood what the situation was.
And it was a, it was a, the change of command ceremony was really a, it was something to behold, and there was a lot of mixed emotions, submerged emotions of elation that this guy was leaving.
No, Bianchi?
Bianchi was leaving, yeah.
Oh, okay, so after two years then Bianchi was reassigned.
Right, and there was quite a lot of speculation on his part.
He was hoping he'd be made Chief of Staff of the Italian Air Force, but he wasn't.
He was put in a major supply position in Rome, Italy, outside of the NATO organization, but strictly in the Italian Air Force.
a shelf assignment for him in his last tour, I suppose.
But it was definitely, I'm sure that it broke the old boy's heart, but didn't break his spirit any.
Right through the change of command ceremony, he was still the same type.
You were happy to see him?
Oh, was I ever happy to see him.
So you had one more year with a man who was a- Very fine person.
Oh, okay.
Very fine.
Okay, now there's a number of questions that I want to ask you about this 1960-1963 NATO assignment.
One is, when were nuclear weapons put in, given to NATO?
Do you remember?
Oh, they were there when I got there in 1960.
Do you remember when they were put in?
Did I get there in 59?
You arrived there in October 1960.
Yeah, 1960.
Oh yeah, you had nuclear capabilities in Italy.
Your airplanes did.

No, not to tell you an Air Force airplane, but we had under our operational control a rotating flight of United States Air Force Tactical Air Command F-100s at Aviano Air Force Base in northern Italy.
that were good nuclear alerts to us, a little nuclear alert all the time.
Now, let's say we had operational command of it.
We didn't give orders for the takeoff of those type of airplanes or conduct their training.
That was done under the commander of the United States Air Forces of Europe.
It was strictly a United States Air Force set up that we spun headquarters.
So it wasn't NATO?

No, well, the training and responsibility was not NATO, but the operational command, and let's say the ordering them on a mission, was the NATO job, which was still the United States Air Force commander at that time, General, was it Norstad?
So NATO, so in other words, well, the Supreme Commander of NATO is an American.
That's right.
That's right, and he has control of the atomic nuclear arsenal.
Now, let's talk about the quality of the force, the quality of the Italians that you were working with, the quality of the Air Force in your area.
Well, in the first place,
The Italian Air Force was manned with old F-84 aircraft.
In fact, obsolete aircraft.
Sure, yeah.
The 84 Sabre jets?
No, no, that's the F-86.
Oh, yeah.
It's an old Thunderbird, I think you call it.
It's a thud, if you ever will.
Okay.
That's an expression we use.
Don't get me mixed up with the F-105 thud, but this airplane was a thud.
Okay.
Just, you know, outdated.
Okay.
Actually...

The range and performance capability of the aircraft, the 84s that the Italian Air Force had, quite frankly, I wonder if they even could get to their targets across the mountains over into, let's say, Romania and that area, and maybe into Yugoslavia, or should we be involved in something like that.
But they had also one squadron of Italian-built tactical aircraft, what do they call it?
It was an Italian-built airplane, and it was jet.
Now these don't jet aircraft, but it had the performance of a P-40.
They were equipped very poorly, definitely inferior equipment, and I was hoping during the time I was over there that maybe we could get better equipment, maybe F-100s, you know.
We did, and they had a troop carrier group of C-119, a horrible airplane.
But crew-wise, generally speaking, the crews with the equipment they had, I think they did a good job.
They certainly tried.
And morale-wise, their morale was good.

They had more of a happy-go-lucky attitude towards life, you know, typical Italians, and we Americans, they seemed, I don't know, they just didn't strike me as being dedicated to the task as much as a typical American would call it.
If there was an attack from the Eastern Bloc countries in Italy, where was your major objective, your targeting objective?
The only ones they had in the Air Forces was these Aviano-based F-100s under the command of the United States Air Force commander, who were then reported to NATO shape commanders.
And they had their specific targets.
Actually, we didn't even get into that planning.
Well, what about a mission?
the Eastern Bloc started to move west.
Well, you're close to the border of Yugoslavia.
What was your mission?
We were prepared, quite frankly, it's a good question.
All you have to do is look at the map.
Sure.
And down in Italy, really the forces that Air South looked for and did the most critical thing was the 6th ATF, Turkey and Greece.
Mm-hmm.
You look at the map, and you've asked me questions that I used to ask myself.
Are we in an air defense role?
And quite frankly, we were.
As a matter of fact, it so turned out that they learned about my air defense background, General Bianchi asked me, but in fact directed me, to prepare an air defense plan for all of Italy.
I sat down and did that while I was over there.
I prepared the air defense plan.
Here are those clunkers.
F84 they'd use for air defense.
But should the invasion come on over, we could get above the Alps, and maybe into Austria area, and we could get over into Yugoslavia, and maybe even get a mission over into Hungary or Romania.
But if we got into Romania, they'd never made it back.
So it's a good question to ask.
So really, it's an air defense posture, quite frankly.
And it so turned out that... Defend Eastern Italy.
That's right.
Well, defend Italy.
Now, the Army, and support the Italian Army, but again, you ask the question, against what?
Now, the Italian Army would be on the ground with tanks and all, well, they're going to have to wait until the Russians get over there where they can get striking distance of them, if you will.
Sure.
So...
But now they did have the Army, the Italian Army had a regiment of Honest John's, a new character.
Of course, it was controlled by the American Honest John outfit.
And they had a range, but quite frankly, those at that time were almost out of the league.
I think the range was 75 miles.
What were they going to get from the emplacements in Italy?
So it's another question.
So the main brunt of the NATO force was probably, still is today, Germany.
Oh, Central.
Absent.
Central for sure.
Historic, it's only sure.
Now, they've made probably some naval operations, but that's the reason that there was another command in the Mediterranean, the Malta, which was strictly a naval, a British naval command, plus
the naval forces, the United States Navy primarily, with Italian, Greek, and Turkish navies integrated under Navy South, NAV South.
And of course their mission would be toward Istanbul.
Oh yeah, fictive naval warfare.
And you don't have a carrier there too.
But if you look back now, strictly the Italian
The Italian Armed Forces and NATO then, as far as I see from an employment standpoint, is picking one of their defense and politically being part of NATO.
How about cooperation on maneuvers?
It must have gone out with maneuvers with other NATO countries.
How good were the maneuvers?
Did the people cooperate?
The only joint maneuvers we had was air defense maneuvers, communication across the Alps with the 4th ATF to pass early warning to one another.
And actually, we even tried to work up joint air defense procedures across the border into France with the French air defense command.
And I actually made trips over there and
coordinating such operations.
And we worked out the procedures, but you didn't have much for joint maneuvers.
Now, we had joint maneuvers with the Italian Army all the time, you know, supporting them and tanks advancing across the Italian countryside where they could along the mountainous roads.
Italian Air Force 84 is flying over and supporting them and giving them protection and all that type of stuff.
Yeah, we had that.
And, you know, did the best.
We had a hole in the mountain for 5th ATF Command Air Control Center, but again, see, it was air defense.
Sure.
Compared to many of your other assignments, this sounds pretty dull.
It was.
You're right.
Not only dull, but for the first two years, miserable.
Now, you were here about the same time France was pulling out of NATO.
No, I came home just about that time, I believe.
I think that happened right after I came home.
Yeah.
I don't even think de Gaulle was president at that time, was he?
I'm not sure.
I'm sorry.
I thought it was 63.
No, as a matter of fact, I remember visiting NATO headquarters in Paris, outside of Paris.
I think it was shortly after I left.
Okay, well.
How'd you get along with the French?
What little I communicated with them and did air defense planning with them, I got along with them all right.
They weren't hard to deal with.
They weren't too interested in dealing with Italians.
They were more interested in talking to me than they were Italians.
Greeks I loved.
What little relations I had with them mainly died when I'd go down to Naples and visit Air South.
The Turks I loved.
The Italian people, I literally love.
The lower-ranking Italians, and generally speaking, most of the Italian Air Force officers, I love.
They're great.
I just didn't like my boss.
In 1963, you were awarded your second star.
What was your feeling on that?
When I learned that, I was visiting...
Air Force headquarters in the Pentagon, and I was with General Swofford, and the promotion list, I was sitting in the visiting general's office.

I knew the list was about to be published, and General Swofford had never said a word to me, but he was sitting in the outer office, reserved for visiting generals, going over some papers, and I was sitting inside by the secretary, you know, waiting for him, and
Uh, in walked a Colonel from Chief Staff's Office right down the hall, and he had the new, brand new Promotion List, Major General Brigadier General gave it to the Secretary.
And, uh, she, she didn't, she knew who I was, but she didn't know anything about whether I'd be on this or not, and she said, maybe you'd be interested in this.
I said, do come on in.
I said, you bet I'm interested in it.
Can I see one of those?
And I grabbed it and made it go down there with Charles Arbonne Jr.
Actually, I felt great.
I immediately turned around, and I didn't even care what John Swofford was doing or how involved he was with the paper writing thing.
I just walked into him and put my hand out.
And I said, thank you very much, John Swofford.
He looked at me.
I said, I just got emotional.
He said, oh.
He says, well, congratulations.
He says, I knew it.
And then I showed it to him.
And I turned around and walked out.
And of course, Doris and the kid were still back in Italy.

And I don't remember, naturally I was happy and elated, and maybe I was a little bit surprised, but I remember reading that OER, and the officer's perspective report where the admiral made that comment, and again, I was a little surprised, but
To a certain extent, I must admit, maybe egotistically, but I did kind of expect it.
And I had about another six or eight months to go, and I was going to be reassigned at the end of the three-year tour.
But later on, General Swofford or somebody made that comment to me that I told you a moment ago.
It's the first time
I think he said his first time Brigadier General in this position, in the Air Force position, has ever been promoted to a Major General on the spot.
So that was quite a compliment to me.
At least I took it that way.
And after that, of course, the Italian General, I replaced General Bianchi with my boss.
when I came back and arrived at the airport.
As a matter of fact, they met me at the airplane to congratulate me.
And all the other colonels and generals in the Italian Air Force knew about it by then, you know, where it got back to then.
Of course, my wife knew it.
So, as a matter of fact, I stepped off the airplane with two stars.
No kidding.
They let you wear two stars back?
Yeah.
Well, it was effective, I think, practically the day they put out the list.
Effective for me.
I forget how it was, but two or three days, you know, is the time we got back.
First of July of 63.
Yeah.
Okay.
Yeah.
First of July of 63, and in August of 63, you were, you switched, you left Italy, were you happy to go?
Oh, yeah.
And you went to
Shaw Air Force Base where you were the Deputy Commander of the 9th Air Force.
And you stayed there for three years.
Right.
Oh, almost three years.
I forget the date.
Yeah.
Well, from August 1963 to January 1966.
What were your responsibilities there?
Well, Deputy Commander, Under the Commander,

At first it was General Koerner, C-O-Y-N-E-R, and it was that time that General Sweeney was commander of TAC, the SAC General, that used to be, I think, his chief of staff, the vice commander of SAC, and for some reason or another they decided to assign him, give him TAC, Tactical Aircraft.

deputy commander of 9th, and my relations, the command channel of course went to General Sweeney and General Corner, so normally all the relationships between those two, but I learned to know General Sweeney as the vice commander of 9th Air Force, and that's where we got in a lot of joint training exercises

some very big and expensive exercises with the United States Army and where we got involved in a lot of controversial discussions with the United States Army as to how we support them and who would have helicopters and troop lifts and air carriers, this type of stuff.
There was a big problem here on helicopters between the Army and the Air Force.
Can you explain that?

Yes, the Army had their helicopters and we had our helicopters and the Army was operating with the idea that they were going to equip and build and design and deploy helicopters armed with such nature that they would really take over air support and give direct air support to their troops when this was rightfully by roles and missions of the United States Air Force.
So really, the roles and missions
was the controversial thing at that time between the Air Force and the United States Army, and I was right in the middle of this.
And in the many exercises we had, I have to give General Sweeney full credit for it.
He was instrumental.
It might very well be that's the reason he was assigned the job.
He was a very adamant, demanding, martinet-type, ruthless general.

far more, in my opinion, than General LeMay, and I'm sure that a lot of this so-called ruthlessness of General LeMay at SAC really stemmed from this man, I feel, because he exhibited as a commander of TAC.
In his dealings with the Army?
In his dealings with the Army, he was a dynamic

man who wouldn't, you know, it wouldn't take no for an answer, and this is my job, and I could very well be that's the reason he was put in there, because we were having a very hard time with the Army and maintaining our position that ground direct air support is an Air Force mission, and you shouldn't have what's now known as attack helicopters with missiles on them, guns, and so forth, and you shouldn't do your
local tactical reconnaissance.
We do that and so forth.
So that's one reason we had all these exercises and that's one reason that the so-called STRYCOM command was organized, Strike Forces was organized and set up as a joint tactical force at

met at the MacDill Air Force Base in Florida, in Tampa, Florida, where an Army commander was commanding it, and he had a deputy who was an Air Force commander, and on the exercises that the Army and the Air Force would have, see, he would command them.
Therefore, he would be the umpire and the referee, let's say, about the developing joint tactics for support of the ground forces and the Air Force and the Army operating together.
And to make a long story short, we had a lot of exercise and a lot of TDY.
And it so turned out that your old Charlie Bond was always tabbed by one General Sweeney as the Air Force component commander of those exercises.
And this is where...
I don't know.
I have a feeling that
I said, I don't possibly know.
He never did tell me except that I got the impression from him he just thought that I was good at it.
Nobody else could do it any better than I could.
Plus the fact that he knew I knew tactical air warfare.
A lot of ways I had almost written a book, if you will, in a lot of ways.
And he knew I was dependable.
I think he knew I didn't particularly care

because the first, just go back a little, the first job I ever was given when I was assigned to that job as vice commander in 9th Air Force was they had a terrible accident down at Eglin Air Force Base by one of the outfits where we were making rocket attacks
on some targets directed by a forward air controller, exercises, you know, developing tactics.
And the airplane came around and fired its rockets into the controller's position and killed one of the pilots there who was, you know, supposed to be the controller and marked the target.
And they were investigating the accident.
I hadn't been to Kamehameha in two weeks.
I got a call from Chief of Staff at TAC that General Sweeney wants you to head up this accident investigation board.

And I headed it up, and I wrote it exactly the way I saw it, and it was critical of training procedures conducted by the Tactical Air Command, which of course was interpreted as critical for General Sweeney, and he didn't like it.
And I think... What did he say to you about it?
He had read it one day when I was visiting,
Well, actually, I was supposed to visit him, you know, and talk to him at his office about the report.
When they called me into the office, we sat down and he looked at it the minute he'd read it all.
He dropped it on the table and said, Charlie, I've got some business coming in.
He says, I'm not going to be able to talk to you about this.
In other words, he was dismissing me.
He didn't want to talk to me.
But it was a little bit accusative of the...
the way General Sweeney had put people down there who, in my opinion, were not properly trained to do this mission, and that's exactly the reason this accident occurred.
Lack of supervision and proper training.
And at that time, General LeMay was Chief of Staff of the Air Force.
Now, I don't know whatever happened.
General LeMay knew me.
And there was my accident.
There was a report signed by Charles R. Bond.
I never heard anything from anybody.
And it went right to LeMay?
Oh, sure, it had to go, sure, you know, Chief of Staff.
And he read it?
Well, if he didn't read it, I'm sure he was briefed on it, and I'm convinced to this day that he knew that Charlie Bond was investigating him.
He had to know that, because the Chief of Safety and the Chief of Staff had to brief him.
Sure.
It was a nasty accident.
But anyway, I don't know, maybe...
He kept me on TV all the time.
It darn near caused a divorce in my family.
Because you were always gone?
I was always gone.
I remember specifically at the end of one joint training exercise we had at Eglin Air Force called Indian River.
He got through with everything.
The exercise was supposed to be over, and I said, well, I'll be going back tomorrow.
And he said, last thing you stated.
But Charlie said, I want you to stay down.
That's all he said.
I don't even remember making a comment, but to me it was, I took it as, I just took it hard.
When did you ever get to see your wife?
Oh yeah, as a matter of fact, my wife, I was gone so much that I made arrangements to have her come down and visit me with the kids.
One time I flew up, got permission to fly a driver down.
But that's, I did a, I did a
I did a commendable job.
I must have because I was continually put back in charge of all the Air Force forces in these joint exercises and I was well respected by my counterparts in the Army and we got along well.
It was terrific experience.
But here again, you know, the idea to keep a vice commander occupied, I guess, so I accepted it.
But it was hard, but I did it.
Concerning the helicopters, especially the Army use of helicopters in Vietnam, who won that battle?
